Bug: linking libxul.so on this toolchain fails with "undefined
reference to `rand'" / "undefined reference to `srand'" for every one
of the ~130 call sites across the tree that use them, even though
every other libc symbol resolves fine -- including malloc, free,
printf, memcpy, and the functionally-identical random()/srandom()
pair, all pulled from the very same libc.so in the very same link.
Isolated testing (relinking libxul.so's exact object list by hand,
swapping in a trivial standalone object that only calls rand()/
random()) confirmed this is specific to the literal symbol names
"rand" and "srand" at this object-file scale/toolchain combination
(GCC 15 / binutils 2.46 / glibc 2.43) -- not to anything Mozilla-
specific, and not fixable by reordering -lc, forcing --allow-shlib-
undefined, using libc.so.6 directly instead of via the ld GROUP()
script, or adding/removing --gc-sections.

Work around it by providing our own rand()/srand() definitions,
implemented as thin wrappers around random()/srandom() (which have
identical semantics and value range to rand()/srand() on glibc:
RAND_MAX == 2^31-1 both ways). Being linked in ahead of libc, these
satisfy every caller directly and the problematic libc symbols are
never looked up at all.
Index: xpcom/build/moz.build
--- a/xpcom/build/moz.build	Thu Jan 08 23:22:45 2015 -0500
+++ b/xpcom/build/moz.build	Sun Jul 12 12:10:24 2026 +0800
@@ -61,6 +61,11 @@
         'NSPRInterposer.cpp',
     ]
 
+if CONFIG['OS_ARCH'] == 'Linux':
+    SOURCES += [
+        'LinuxRandCompat.c',
+    ]
+
 # FileLocation.cpp and Omnijar.cpp cannot be built in unified mode because they
 # use plarena.h.
 SOURCES += [
Index: xpcom/build/LinuxRandCompat.c
--- /dev/null	Thu Jan 01 00:00:00 1970 +0000
+++ b/xpcom/build/LinuxRandCompat.c	Sun Jul 12 12:10:24 2026 +0800
@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@
+/* This Source Code Form is subject to the terms of the Mozilla Public
+ * License, v. 2.0. If a copy of the MPL was not distributed with this
+ * file, You can obtain one at http://mozilla.org/MPL/2.0/. */
+
+/* On this Linux toolchain, the final libxul.so link fails to resolve
+ * plain calls to libc's rand()/srand() ("undefined reference to
+ * `rand'") even though every other libc symbol -- including the
+ * functionally-identical random()/srandom() -- resolves fine from the
+ * same libc.so in the same link. Providing our own definitions here
+ * (linked in ahead of libc) sidesteps whatever is going on with those
+ * two specific symbol names. random()/srandom() have the same value
+ * range and semantics as rand()/srand() on glibc (RAND_MAX == 2^31-1
+ * both ways), so this is a value-for-value equivalent replacement.
+ */
+
+#include <stdlib.h>
+
+int
+rand(void)
+{
+  return (int)random();
+}
+
+void
+srand(unsigned int aSeed)
+{
+  srandom(aSeed);
+}
